[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Appendix B[bold]Examples of stations serving isolated communities[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Berney Arms[bold] (Norfolk) on the Wherry Line.  No road access to this isolated community on the Norfolk Broads.  Access by footpath across Halv
[normal]e
[normal]rgate marshes or by boat.  
[normal]Two trains a day each way call on request and five on Sundays.
[normal]Causeland [bold](Cornwall) 
[normal]on the Looe Valley line.  Remote community linked by narrow lanes.  No regular bus service.  Ten trains a day from Liskeard call on request. 
[normal]Chathill [bold](Northumberland) on East Coast Main Line.  Terminus of local 
[normal]train 
[normal]service from Newcastle twice a day
[normal].  O
[normal]ne bus a week (Thursday) provides a shopping trip to Alnwick (no rail connection). 
[normal] 
[normal]Commondale [bold](North Yorkshire) on Esk Valley Line.  
[normal]Serves an isolated community within the North York Moors.  
[normal]Four trains a day u
[normal]sed by walkers
[normal],
[normal] and by local residents to a
[normal]ccess work and services. One bus a week (Wednesday) provides a shopping trip to Stokesley and Northallerton. Population 179 (2011)
[normal]Corrour[bold] (Highland Region), on West Highl
[normal]a
[normal]nd Line.  
[normal]Ten miles from the nearest public 
[normal]road.  Station accessible by footpath 
[normal]only.  Very isolated
[normal],
[normal] but frequented by walkers
[normal] and visitors
[normal] to the Station House restaurant
[normal].
[normal]  
